# Upwork Proposal — humanized pitch writer in Khaled's voice

The "win the call without sounding like every other freelancer" engine. Most AI automation freelancers send corporate templates that get ignored. This skill writes the way Khaled actually pitches — leads with the punch, drops one real proof point, and asks one question. Closes calls, not just sends them.

**Why this exists:** Khaled has closed 2 Upwork clients in the AI automation niche. The pattern that worked: read the job post carefully, open with ONE specific thing that proves you actually read it, mention ONE relevant win (not a list), end with ONE clarifying question or offer. Templates fail because clients see them every day. This skill replicates the pattern that worked.

---

## When to run

- Khaled or a viewer pastes an Upwork job post (or URL) and wants a proposal.
- Anyone watching the YouTube tutorial who wants to apply to AI automation jobs.
- Quick rewrite of a proposal that's reading too corporate.

**Don't run when** the job is wildly off-niche (graphic design, copywriting only, etc.) — flag it and stop. We pitch AI automation, voice agents, Make.com, n8n, Claude API, Vapi, scraping, outreach systems. That's it.

---

## Inputs

1. **The job post** — paste full text, OR paste an Upwork URL (use WebFetch to pull the post).
2. **(Optional) Which win to anchor on** — if Khaled (or the user) wants to highlight a specific past project. Otherwise the skill picks the most relevant one from the win library below.
3. **(Optional) Hourly target or fixed-bid range** — if mentioned, the proposal includes it. Otherwise stays silent on price.

If only a URL is given, WebFetch it. If WebFetch fails (Upwork blocks scraping sometimes), ask the user to paste the post text instead.

---

## Khaled's voice — hard rules

### Tone
- **Lead with the punch.** Line 1 is something specific from THEIR post. Not "Hi, I'm Khaled."
- **One real win only.** Don't list. Pick the most relevant.
- **No corporate phrases.** Banned: "I hope this finds you well", "I came across your post", "I would be delighted to", "I am writing to express", "Please find attached", "Looking forward to hearing from you."
- **Casual but sharp.** Like explaining to a smart friend over coffee.
- **120 words max. Hard cap.** Anything longer loses the read.
- **Never em-dashes.** Use periods, commas, or just stop the sentence.
- **End with ONE question or ONE concrete offer.** Not both. Not "let me know if you have any questions" (everyone says that, means nothing).

### Structure (the 5-line shape that works)

```
Line 1 — The specific hook. ONE thing from their post.
         "Saw you're using Make.com for the trigger but need n8n on the
          processing side — is that because of the loop limit?"

Line 2 — The win. ONE relevant past project, 1 sentence.
         "I built something close last year for a French real-estate agency:
          inbound leads → SMS qualifier → calendar booking on Vapi."

Line 3 — Why it maps. 1 sentence connecting your win to their problem.
         "Same shape as yours — the bottleneck is going to be the handoff
          between platforms, not the AI."

Line 4 — (Optional) Proof / portfolio link. ONE link if relevant.
         "Quick demo here: [link]"  OR skip this line entirely.

Line 5 — The close. ONE question OR one concrete next step.
         "Want me to send the architecture as a Loom before you decide?"
         OR
         "Free 15 min this week to walk through your current flow?"
```

Total: 80–120 words. Anything shorter and it reads dismissive. Anything longer and it gets skipped.

